<subSubSection id="CAAE6535FFE2FF89FF7BFAE6FC61FA71" pageId="94" pageNumber="95" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="820B36BEFFE2FF89FF7BFAE6FE82FAEF" blockId="94.[189,303,1338,1364]" box="[189,303,1338,1364]" pageId="94" pageNumber="95">
<heading id="D94381D2FFE2FF89FF7BFAE6FE82FAEF" bold="true" box="[189,303,1338,1364]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="94" pageNumber="95" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B0C0EAACFFE2FF89FF7BFAE6FE82FAEF" bold="true" box="[189,303,1338,1364]" pageId="94" pageNumber="95">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="820B36BEFFE2FF89FF7BFAB4FC61FA71" blockId="94.[189,1399,1384,1482]" pageId="94" pageNumber="95">
Described from Florence, this species was re-collected at Monte Amiata, considerably further south, by 
<bibRefCitation id="E6254B4FFFE2FF89FF7BFA50FECEFA1D" author="Spelda J." box="[189,355,1420,1446]" pageId="94" pageNumber="95" pagination="5 - 48" refId="ref39559" refString="Spelda J. 2008. The genus Pyrgocyphosoma Verhoeff, 1910 (Diplopoda, Chordeumatida: Craspedosomatidae): New aspects on systematics, distribution and ecology. Schubartiana 3: 5 - 48." type="journal article" year="2008">Spelda (2008)</bibRefCitation>
who speculated that the 
<typeStatus id="5D0F881CFFE2FF89FD4AFA51FD12FA1C" box="[652,703,1421,1447]" pageId="94" pageNumber="95">type</typeStatus>
locality might not have been precise or that this species is widely distributed in the lower parts of 
<collectingRegion id="4070F85CFFE2FF89FD4BFA6CFD42FA71" box="[653,751,1456,1482]" country="Italy" name="Toscana" pageId="94" pageNumber="95">Tuscany</collectingRegion>
south of Florence.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
